"/5/ Perhaps, however, a case could be put where the riding was so manifestly dangerous that it would be murder.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"To recur to an example which has been used already for another purpose: When a workman flings down a stone or piece of timber into the street, and kills a man; this may be either misadventure, manslaughter, or murder, according to the circumstances under which the original act was done: if it were in a country village, where few passengers are, and he calls out to all people to have a care, it is misadventure only; but if it were in London, or other populous town, where people are continually passing, it is manslaughter, though he gives loud warning; and murder, if he knows of their passing, and gives no warning at all.",1,0,0,0,0,0
/6/ The law of manslaughter contains another doctrine [61] which should be referred to in order to complete the understanding of the general principles of the criminal law.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"This doctrine is, that provocation may reduce an offence which would otherwise have been murder to manslaughter.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"According to current morality, a man is not so much to blame for an act done under the disturbance of great excitement, caused by a wrong done to himself, as when he is calm.",1,1,1,1,0,0
"The law is made to govern men through their motives, and it must, therefore, take their mental constitution into account.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"It might be urged, on the other side, that, if the object of punishment is prevention, the heaviest punishment should be threatened where the strongest motive is needed to restrain; and primitive legislation seems sometimes to have gone on that principle.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"But if any threat will restrain a man in a passion, a threat of less than death will be sufficient, and therefore the extreme penalty has been thought excessive.",0,0,0,0,0,0
At the same time the objective nature of legal standards is shown even here.,0,0,0,0,0,0
The mitigation does not come from the fact that the defendant was beside himself with rage.,1,1,1,1,1,1
It is not enough that he had grounds which would have had the same effect on every man of his standing and education.,1,1,0,1,1,0
"The most insulting words are not provocation, although to this day, and still more when the law was established, many people would rather die than suffer them without action.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"There must be provocation sufficient to justify the passion, and the law decides on general considerations what provocations are sufficient.",0,0,0,0,0,0
