"/1/ Accordingly, although that decision was the main authority relied on for the hundred years between it and Coggs v. Bernard whenever a peculiar responsibility was imposed upon bailees, we find that sometimes an assumpsit was laid as in the early precedents, /2/ or more frequently that the bailee was alleged to be a common bargeman, or common carrier, or the like, without much reference to the special nature of the tort in question; and that the true bearing of the allegation was sometimes lost sight of.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"At first, however, there were only some slight signs of confusion in the language of one or two cases, and if the duty was conceived to fall within the principle of Southcote's Case, pleaders did not always allege the common or public calling which was held unnecessary.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"/3/ But they also adopted other devices from the precedents in case, or to strengthen an obligation which they did not well understand.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"Chief Justice Popham had sanctioned a distinction between paid and unpaid bailees, hence it was deemed prudent to lay a reward.",1,0,0,0,0,0
Negligence was of course averred; and finally it became frequent to allege an obligation by the law and custom of the realm.,1,0,0,0,0,0
This last deserves a little further attention.,0,0,0,0,0,0
There is no writ in the Register alleging any special obligation of common carriers by the custom of the realm.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"But the writ against innkeepers did lay a duly by the [188] law and custom of England, and it was easy to adopt the phrase.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"The allegation did not so much imply the existence of a special principle, as state a proposition of law in the form which was then usual.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"There are other writs of trespass which allege a common-law duty in the same way, and others again setting forth a statutory obligation.",0,0,0,0,0,0
/1/ So the judges were sworn to execute justice according to law and the custom of England.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"/2/ The duties of a common carrier, so far as the earlier evidence goes, were simply those of bailees in general, coupled with the liabilities generally attached to the exercise of a public calling.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"The word common addressed itself only to the latter point, as has been shown above.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"This is further illustrated by the fact that, when the duty was thus set forth, it was not alleged as an obligation peculiar to common carriers as such, but was laid as the custom of law of common hoymen, or lightermen, &c., according to the business of the party concerned.",1,0,0,0,0,0
