"Why is the repugnancy between the two terms,--first, that the thing sold is the contents of these barrels, and, second, that it is mackerel--fatal to the existence of a contract?",1,0,0,0,0,0
"It is because each of those terms goes to the very root and essence of the contract, /1/--because to compel the buyer to take something answering to one, but not to the other requirement, would be holding him to do a substantially different thing from what he promised, and because a promise to take one and the same thing answering to both requirements is therefore contradictory in a substantial matter.",1,1,1,1,1,1
"It has been seen that the law does not go on any merely logical ground, and does not hold that every slight repugnancy will make a contract even voidable.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"But, on the other hand, when the repugnancy is between terms which are both essential, it is fatal to the very existence of the contract.",0,0,0,0,0,0
