"/2/ Another principle of dependency to be drawn from the form of the contract itself is, that performance of the promise on one side may be manifestly intended to furnish the means for performing the promise on the other.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"If a tenant should promise to make repairs, and the landlord should promise to furnish him wood for the purpose, it is believed that at the present day, whatever may have been the old decisions, the tenant's duty to repair would be dependent upon the landlord's furnishing the material when required.",1,1,1,1,1,1
/3/ [337] Another case of a somewhat exceptional kind is where a party to a bilateral contract agrees to do certain things and to give security for his performance.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Here it is manifest good-sense to hold giving the security a condition of performance on the other side, if it be possible.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"For the requirement of security shows that the party requiring it was not content to rely on the simple promise of the other side, which he would be compelled to do if he had to perform before the security was given, and thus the very object of requiring it would be defeated.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"/1/ This last case suggests what is very forcibly impressed on any one who studies the cases,--that, after all, the most important element of decision is not any technical, or even any general principle of contracts, but a consideration of the nature of the particular transaction as a practical matter.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"A promises B to do a day's work for two dollars, and B promises A to pay two dollars for a day's work.",1,0,0,0,0,0
There the two promises cannot be performed at the same time.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"The work will take all day, the payment half a minute.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"How are you to decide which is to be done first, that is to say, which promise is dependent upon performance on the other side?",0,0,0,0,0,0
It is only by reference to the habits of the community and to convenience.,0,0,0,0,0,0
It is not enough to say that on the principle of equivalency a man is not presumed to intend to pay for a thing until he has it.,1,1,1,1,0,0
