Thou handest it over to me by law; and I [360] take it from thee by law.',1,0,0,0,0,0
"Afterwards, these witnesses come before the court, and bear witness to the transfer in like words: He handed over to him then this suit, with all the proofs and proceedings which belonged to the suit, he handed it over to him to plead and to settle, and to make use of all rights, as though he were the rightful next of kin.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"Thorgeir handed it over lawfully, and Mord took it lawfully.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"The suit went on, notwithstanding the change of hands, as if the next of kin were plaintiff.",0,0,0,0,0,0
This is shown by a further step in the proceedings.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"The defendant challenges two of the court, on the ground of their connection with Mord, the transferee, by blood and by baptism.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"But Mord replies that this is no good challenge; for he challenged them not for their kinship to the true plaintiff, the next of kin, but for their kinship to him who pleaded the suit.",1,0,0,0,0,0
And the other side had to admit that Mord was right in his law.,1,1,1,0,1,0
I now turn from the German to the Roman sources.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"These have the closest connection with the argument, because much of the doctrine to be found there has been transplanted unchanged into modern law.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"The early Roman law only recognized as relatives those who would have been members of the same patriarchal family, and under the same patriarchal authority, had the common ancestor survived.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"As wives passed into the families of their husbands, and lost all connection with that in which they were born, relationship through females was altogether excluded.",1,0,0,0,0,0
The heir was one who traced his relationship to the deceased through males alone.,1,1,1,1,1,1
With the advance of civilization this rule was changed.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"The praetor gave the benefits of the inheritance to the blood relations, although they were not heirs, and could [361] not be admitted to the succession according to the ancient law.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"/1/ But the change was not brought about by repealing the old law, which still subsisted under the name of the jus civile.",1,0,0,0,0,0
The new principle was accommodated to the old forms by a fiction.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"The blood relation could sue on the fiction that he was an heir, although he was not one in fact.",1,1,0,1,1,0
"/2/ One the early forms of instituting an heir was a sale of the familia or headship of the family to the intended heir, with all its rights and duties.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"/3/ This sale of the universitas was afterwards extended beyond the case of inheritance to that of bankruptcy, when it was desired to put the bankrupt's property into the hands of a trustee for distribution.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"This trustee also could make use of the fiction, and sue as if he had been the bankrupt's heir.",0,0,0,0,0,0
/4/ We are told by one of the great jurisconsults that in general universal successors stand in the place of heirs.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"/5/ The Roman heir, with one or two exceptions, was always a universal successor; and the fiction of heirship, as such, could hardly be used with propriety except to enlarge the sphere of universal successions.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"So far as it extended, however, all the consequences attached to the original fiction of identity between heir and ancestor followed as of course.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"[362] To recur to the case of rights acquired by prescription, every universal successor could add the time of his predecessor's adverse use to his own in order to make out the right.",1,1,1,1,1,1
"There was no addition, legally speaking, but one continuous possession.",0,0,0,0,0,0
The express fiction of inheritance perhaps stopped here.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"But when a similar joinder of times was allowed between a legatee or devisee (legatarius) and his testator, the same explanation was offered.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"It was said, that, when a specific thing was left to a person by will, so far as concerned having the benefit of the time during which the testator had been in possession for the purpose of acquiring a title, the legatee was in a certain sense quasi an heir.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"/1/ Yet a legatarius was not a universal successor, and for most purposes stood in marked contrast with such successors.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"/2/ Thus the strict law of inheritance had made the notion familiar that one man might have the advantage of a position filled by another, although it was not filled, or was only partially filled, by himself; and the second fiction, by which the privileges of a legal heir in this respect as well as others had been extended to other persons, broke down the walls which might otherwise have confined those privileges to a single case.",1,1,1,1,0,0
"A new conception was introduced into the law, and there was nothing to hinder its further application.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"As has been shown, it was applied in terms to a sale of the universitas for business purposes, and to at least one case where the succession was confined to a single specific thing.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Why, then, might not every gift or sale be regarded as a succession, so far as to insure the same advantages?",0,0,0,0,0,0
"[363] The joinder of times to make out a title was soon allowed between buyer and seller, and I have no doubt, from the language always used by the Roman lawyers, that it was arrived at in the way I have suggested.",1,0,0,0,0,0
A passage from Scaevola (B. C. 30) will furnish sufficient proof.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Joinder of possessions, he says, that is, the right to add the time of one's predecessor's holding to one's own, clearly belongs to those who succeed to the place of others, whether by contract or by will: for heirs and those who are treated as holding the place of successors are allowed to add their testator's possession to their own.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"Accordingly, if you sell me a slave I shall have the benefit of your holding.",1,0,0,0,0,0
/1/ The joinder of times is given to those who succeed to the place of another.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Ulpian cites a like phrase from a jurisconsult of the time of the Antonines,--to whose place I have succeeded by inheritance, or purchase, or any other right.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"/2/ Succedere in locum aliorum, like sustinere personam, is an expression of the Roman lawyers for those continuations of one man's legal position by another of which the type was the succession of heir to ancestor.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Suecedere alone is used in the sense of inherit, /3/ and successio in that of inheritance.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"/4/ The succession par excellence was the inheritance; and it is believed that scarcely any instance will be found in the Roman sources where succession does not convey that analogy, and indicate the partial [364] assumption, at least, of a persona formerly sustained by another.",0,0,0,0,0,0
It clearly does so in the passage before us.,0,0,0,0,0,0
But the succession which admits a joinder of times is not hereditary succession alone.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"In the passage which has been cited Scaevola says that it may be by contract or purchase, as well as by inheritance or will.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"It may be singular, as well as universal.",0,0,0,0,0,0
The jurists often mention antithetically universal successions and those confined to a single specific thing.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Ulpian says that a man succeeds to another's place, whether his succession be universal or to the single object.",1,1,1,1,0,0
"/1/ If further evidence were wanting for the present argument, it would be found in another expression of Ulpian's.",1,0,0,0,0,0
He speaks of the benefit of joinder as derived from the persona of the grantor.,0,0,0,0,0,0
He to whom a thing is granted shall have the benefit of joinder from the persona of his grantor.,1,1,0,1,1,0
/2/ A benefit cannot be derived from a persona except by sustaining it.,1,0,0,0,0,0
"It farther appears pretty plainly from Justinian's Institutes and the Digest, that the benefit was not extended to purchasers in all cases until a pretty late period.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"/3/ Savigny very nearly expressed the truth when he said, somewhat broadly, that every accessio, for whatever purpose, presupposes nothing else than a relation of juridical [365] succession between the previous and present possessor.",1,1,1,1,1,1
For succession does not apply to possession by itself.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"/1/ And I may add, by way of further explanation, that every relation of juridical succession presupposes either an inheritance or a relation to which, so far as it extends, the analogies of the inheritance may be applied.",0,0,0,0,0,0
The way of thinking which led to the accessio or joinder of times is equally visible in other cases.,0,0,0,0,0,0
The time during which a former owner did not use an casement was imputed to the person who had succeeded to his place.,1,1,1,1,1,1
"/2/ The defence that the plaintiff had sold and delivered the thing in controversy was available not only to the purchaser, but to his heirs or to a second purchaser, even before delivery to him, against the successors of the seller, whether universal or only to the thing in question.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"/3/ If one used a way wrongfully as against the predecessor in title, it was wrongful as against the successor, whether by inheritance, purchase, or any other right.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"/4/ The formal oath of a party to an action was conclusive in favor of his successors, universal or singular.",0,0,0,0,0,0
/5/ Successors by purchase or gift had the [366] benefit of agreements made with the vendor.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"/1/ A multitude of general expressions show that for most purposes, whether of action or defence, the buyer stood in the shoes of the seller, to use the metaphor of our own law.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"/2/ And what is more important than the result, which often might have been reached by other ways, the language and analogies are drawn throughout from the succession to the inheritance.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Thus understood, there could not have been a succession between a person dispossessed of a thing against his will and the wrongful possessor.",0,0,0,0,0,0
Without the element of consent there is no room for the analogy just explained.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Accordingly, it is laid down that there is no joinder of times when the possession is wrongful, /3/ and the only enumerated means of succeeding in rem are by will, sale, gift, or some other right.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"The argument now returns to the English law, fortified with some general conclusions.",0,0,0,0,0,0
