/6/ So Paulus [384] speaks of such rights as being accessory to bodies.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"And thus, adds Godefroi, rights may belong to inanimate things.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"/1/ It easily followed from all this that a sale of the dominant estate carried existing easements, not because the buyer succeeded to the place of the seller, but because land is bound to land.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"/2/ All these figures import that land is capable of having rights, as Austin recognizes.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Indeed, he even says that the land is erected into a legal or fictitious person, and is styled 'praedium dominans.'",0,0,0,0,0,0
"/3/ But if this means anything more than to explain what is implied by the Roman metaphors, it goes too far.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"The dominant estate was never erected into a legal person, either by conscious fiction or as a result of primitive beliefs.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"/4/ It could not sue or be sued, like a ship in the admiralty.",0,0,0,0,0,0
